	doi = {10.1111/j.1541-0072.1984.tb00480.x},
	abstract = {Nearly all twentieth century Presidents of the U.S., from Theodore Roosevelt onward, have tried to lead public opinion, to influence policy preferences of citizens of the U.S. Roosevelt had mobilized every available resource of press, radio and personal speech making to build a popular support for his legislation. Scholars in the past have debated on the substance of this development; however, have not questioned its impact upon the public. Instances epitomize that policy preferences have been altered with the change of executives. The article studies this impact in context to policy preferences among citizens of the U.S., based on data collected on national opinion surveys conducted by various organizations between 1935 and 1980. The study concludes that the U.S. Presidents, who have been popular, have been able to affect public opinion.},
